         <abstract>
            <p>Let $UVW$ be a triangle with vertices $U, V$, and $W$. It is "bisected" as follows: choose a longest edge (say $VW$) of $UVW$, and let $A$ be the midpoint of $VW$. The $UVW$ gives birth to two daughter triangles $UVA$ and $UWA$. Continue this bisection process forever. We prove that the infinite family of triangles so obtained falls into finitely many similarity classes, and we obtain sharp estimates for the longest $j$th generation edge.</p>
          </abstract>
